1
00:00:35,640 --> 00:00:38,200
(TYPEWRITER LOADING)

2
00:00:47,200 --> 00:00:49,395
(TYPEWRITER CLACKING)

3
00:00:56,400 --> 00:00:58,470
England
1935

4
00:01:02,040 --> 00:01:04,110
(TYPEWRITER CLACKING)

5
00:02:10,200 --> 00:02:11,952
(WOMEN TALKING)

6
00:02:13,880 --> 00:02:16,155
-I finished my play.
-Well done.

7
00:02:16,240 --> 00:02:17,229
Have you seen Mummy?

8
00:02:17,320 --> 00:02:19,072
Well, she'll be in the drawing room, I expect.

9
00:02:19,160 --> 00:02:22,357
I hope you're not gonna be getting under
our feet today, Miss Briony.

10
00:02:22,440 --> 00:02:24,829
We got a dinner for 10 to prepare.

11
00:02:36,280 --> 00:02:40,034
-Hello, pal, I hear you're putting on a play.
-Who told you?

12
00:02:40,120 --> 00:02:41,473
Jungle drums.

13
00:02:42,760 --> 00:02:46,548
-Will you come and see it?
-I'm not sure that would be quite...

14
00:02:46,640 --> 00:02:47,755
Why don't you let me read it?

15
00:02:47,840 --> 00:02:50,149
You used to make me those beautiful
bound copies of all your stories.

16
00:02:50,240 --> 00:02:52,435
-I've kept them all.
-I still want you to come.

17
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:55,353
-Let's see.
-I have to go now.

18
00:03:00,240 --> 00:03:01,832
Mummy, I need you!

19
00:03:05,680 --> 00:03:10,800
Stupendous. It's stupendous, darling.
Your first play.

20
00:03:10,880 --> 00:03:12,472
Do you think so?
Do you think Leon will like it?

21
00:03:12,560 --> 00:03:14,755
Well, of course he will.

22
00:03:14,840 --> 00:03:17,434
The Trials of Arabella, by Briony Tallis.

23
00:03:27,680 --> 00:03:29,318
-BRIONY: Cee.
-Yes?

24
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:32,956
What do you think it would feel like
to be someone else?

25
00:03:33,040 --> 00:03:35,110
CECILIA: Cooler, I should hope.

26
00:03:35,200 --> 00:03:37,760
-I'm worried about the play.
-I'm sure it's a masterpiece.

27
00:03:37,840 --> 00:03:40,638
But we only have the afternoon to rehearse.
What if the twins can't act?

28
00:03:40,720 --> 00:03:43,280
You have to be nice to them.
I wonder how'd you feel if your mother

29
00:03:43,360 --> 00:03:47,114
had run off with Mr What's-his-name
who reads the news on the wireless?

30
00:03:47,840 --> 00:03:50,479
Perhaps I should have written Leon a story.

31
00:03:50,560 --> 00:03:53,711
If you write a story, you only have to
say the word "castle," and you could see

32
00:03:53,800 --> 00:03:56,519
the towers and the woods
and the village below, but...

33
00:03:56,600 --> 00:03:59,398
In a play, it's...

34
00:03:59,480 --> 00:04:02,517
It all depends on other people.

35
00:04:03,080 --> 00:04:04,718
-Cee.
-Yes?

36
00:04:06,160 --> 00:04:08,515
Why don't you talk to Robbie any more?

37
00:04:08,600 --> 00:04:11,751
I do.
We just move in different circles, that's all.

38
00:04:16,560 --> 00:04:18,551
(WHEELBARROW RATTLING)

39
00:04:24,240 --> 00:04:26,708
-Do we have to do a play?
-Why do we have to?

40
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:29,598
-It's to celebrate my brother Leon's visit.
-PIERROT: I hate plays.

41
00:04:29,680 --> 00:04:31,910
-JACKSON: So do l.
-How can you hate plays?

42
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:35,037
-It's just showing off.
-You'll be in this play or you'll get a clout.

43
00:04:35,120 --> 00:04:38,032
-And I'll tell the parents.
-JACKSON: You're not allowed to clout us.

44
00:04:38,120 --> 00:04:41,669
We're guests in this house. And what did
the parents say we were to make ourselves?

45
00:04:41,760 --> 00:04:43,398
-Well, Pierrot?
-Amenable.

46
00:04:43,480 --> 00:04:45,277
-Jackson?
-Amenable.

47
00:04:45,360 --> 00:04:46,998
Amenable, that's right.

48
00:04:49,160 --> 00:04:51,276
Now, Briony, what's your play about?

49
00:04:51,960 --> 00:04:55,157
Well, it's about how

50
00:04:55,400 --> 00:04:58,358
love is all very well,
but you have to be sensible.

51
00:04:58,480 --> 00:05:00,391
-I suppose you're going to be Arabella.
-Well, not necessarily.

52
00:05:00,480 --> 00:05:02,869
-In that case, do you mind if I play her?
-PIERROT: Lola was in the school play.

53
00:05:02,960 --> 00:05:06,999
Do say yes. It'd be the first decent thing
to happen to me in months.

54
00:05:07,880 --> 00:05:09,632
Well, yes, all right.

55
00:05:11,240 --> 00:05:12,798
I suppose we should start by reading it.

56
00:05:12,880 --> 00:05:15,838
If you're going to be Arabella, then I'll be
the director, thank you very much.

57
00:05:15,920 --> 00:05:17,035
Sorry.

58
00:05:20,080 --> 00:05:21,911
I'm going to do the prologue.

59
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:25,514
"Prologue.

60
00:05:26,640 --> 00:05:29,200
"This is the tale of spontaneous Arabella,

61
00:05:29,280 --> 00:05:31,919
"who ran away with an extrinsic fellow.

62
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,468
"It grieved her parents to see their firstborn

63
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:36,471
"evanesce from her home
to go to Eastbourne."

64
00:05:36,560 --> 00:05:37,549
(DOOR CREAKS)

65
00:05:37,640 --> 00:05:38,629
Yes?

66
00:05:41,280 --> 00:05:44,909
-Nothing. Just thought I'd watch.
-BRIONY: Rehearsals are private, I'm afraid.

67
00:05:45,000 --> 00:05:47,036
You can see the play this evening.

68
00:05:47,120 --> 00:05:50,237
-I'll have to work then.
-Well, I'm sorry, Danny.

69
00:05:50,600 --> 00:05:53,068
JACKSON: Can we go for a swim now?
PIERROT: Yes, yes, yes!

70
00:05:53,160 --> 00:05:57,153
-No, I don't really think there's time!
-PIERROT: Cecilia will let us.

71
00:05:57,280 --> 00:06:00,113
I'm sure a half-hour break
would do us all good.

72
00:06:00,200 --> 00:06:02,316
PIERROT: Cecilia? Cecilia!

73
00:06:03,880 --> 00:06:05,074
Cecilia!

74
00:06:11,280 --> 00:06:12,793
(BEE BUZZING)

75
00:06:29,800 --> 00:06:30,949
(BUZZING)

76
00:06:34,120 --> 00:06:35,348
(GASPS)

77
00:06:53,520 --> 00:06:54,555
(GASPS)

78
00:06:56,440 --> 00:06:58,032
(PANTING)

79
00:08:06,720 --> 00:08:11,236
Cecilia! Cecilia, Cecilia.
Please, can we go for a swim, Cecilia?

80
00:08:11,320 --> 00:08:14,596
Yes, I don't see why not.
Don't go out of your depth!

81
00:09:27,200 --> 00:09:30,033
Can you do me
one of your Bolshevik roll-ups?

82
00:09:35,680 --> 00:09:38,911
-CECILIA: Beautiful day.
-I suppose so. Too hot for me.

83
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:42,718
-Are you enjoying your book?
-No, not really.

84
00:09:42,800 --> 00:09:43,835
It gets better.

85
00:09:44,320 --> 00:09:46,390
I prefer Fielding any day.

86
00:09:49,600 --> 00:09:51,670
Much more passionate.

87
00:10:04,640 --> 00:10:07,473
-Leon's coming down today, did you know?
-I heard a rumour.

88
00:10:07,560 --> 00:10:10,393
He's bringing a friend with him.
It's Paul Marshall, the chocolate millionaire.

89
00:10:10,480 --> 00:10:12,994
-Are the flowers for him?
-Why shouldn't they be?

90
00:10:13,080 --> 00:10:15,196
Leon says he's very charming.

91
00:10:17,400 --> 00:10:19,994
The Old Man telephoned last night.
He says you're planning on being a doctor.

92
00:10:20,080 --> 00:10:22,196
-I'm thinking about it, yes.
-Another six years of student life.

93
00:10:22,280 --> 00:10:24,316
-How else do you become a doctor?
-You could get a fellowship, now,

94
00:10:24,400 --> 00:10:25,913
-couldn't you? With your First?
-I don't want to teach.

95
00:10:28,040 --> 00:10:30,315
I said I'd pay your father back.

96
00:10:33,800 --> 00:10:35,995
That's not what I meant at all.

97
00:10:44,120 --> 00:10:45,758
-Let me help with that.
-No, I'm all right, thanks.

98
00:10:45,840 --> 00:10:47,990
-Take the flowers. Take the flowers.
-I'm all right. I'm all right.

99
00:10:52,520 --> 00:10:54,590
Oh, you idiot.

100
00:10:56,400 --> 00:10:58,277
Do you realise that's probably
the most valuable thing we own?

101
00:10:58,360 --> 00:11:00,237
Not any more, it isn't.

102
00:11:01,880 --> 00:11:03,154
Careful!

103
00:12:19,080 --> 00:12:20,115
I'm...

104
00:13:30,400 --> 00:13:31,913
(CAR HORN HONKING)

105
00:13:38,720 --> 00:13:40,153
LEON: Hello, Robbie!

106
00:13:45,320 --> 00:13:47,276
No need to encourage him.

107
00:13:58,160 --> 00:13:59,195
Cee?

108
00:14:02,960 --> 00:14:03,995
Mother?

109
00:14:06,400 --> 00:14:09,676
-Where is everyone, Danny?
-I don't know, sir.

110
00:14:09,800 --> 00:14:12,075
DANNY: Sir.
LEON: Gasping for a drink.

111
00:14:14,960 --> 00:14:16,757
-Will you have one?
-PAUL: Rather.

112
00:14:17,840 --> 00:14:19,273
-Whisky?
-Please.

113
00:14:23,800 --> 00:14:25,358
-Leon!
-Here she is.

114
00:14:25,440 --> 00:14:30,116
CECILIA: Oh, I've missed you.
I've been going completely doolally up here.

115
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:33,590
-This is my sister, Cecilia. Paul Marshall.
-I've heard an awful lot about you.

116
00:14:33,680 --> 00:14:35,830
-Likewise.
-LEON: Where are we putting him?

117
00:14:35,920 --> 00:14:39,117
In the blue room. Mother's lying down,
she's got one of her migraines.

118
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:41,509
I'm not surprised, with this heat.

119
00:14:43,800 --> 00:14:46,314
It's the big room next to the nursery.

120
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:52,874
Is the Old Man staying in town?

121
00:14:52,960 --> 00:14:55,520
LEON: Looks like it.
Some sort of rush on at the Ministry.

122
00:14:55,840 --> 00:14:58,195
(THUDDING)

123
00:15:11,600 --> 00:15:14,717
PIERROT: So aren't we doing the play?
LOLA: No.

124
00:15:14,800 --> 00:15:17,598
-JACKSON: Why not?
-Don't ask me.

125
00:15:19,480 --> 00:15:21,198
PIERROT: I don't like it here.

126
00:15:22,720 --> 00:15:24,278
PAUL: There's always a problem
when a new brand comes about.

127
00:15:24,360 --> 00:15:26,191
The remarketing, the re-packaging,
the re-shaping.

128
00:15:26,280 --> 00:15:29,272
Even the re-flavouring in some cases,
or whole new technology.

129
00:15:29,760 --> 00:15:32,638
I think our main challenge is whether or not
to launch the new Amo Bar.

130
00:15:32,920 --> 00:15:36,276
The Army Amo. Do you see? Pass the Amo?

131
00:15:36,440 --> 00:15:37,634
(PAUL CHUCKLES)

132
00:15:37,720 --> 00:15:39,039
My source at the Ministry is very reliable,

133
00:15:39,120 --> 00:15:41,429
I used to clean his shoes at Harrow,
informs me we have a good chance

134
00:15:41,520 --> 00:15:43,397
of including it
in the standard issue ration pack.

135
00:15:43,800 --> 00:15:46,234
Which means that I'd have to open
at least three more factories.

136
00:15:46,320 --> 00:15:48,515
More if they bring in conscription,
which I say is bound to happen

137
00:15:48,600 --> 00:15:50,033
if Herr Hitler doesn't pipe down.

138
00:15:50,120 --> 00:15:52,190
He's about as likely to do that as buy shares

139
00:15:52,280 --> 00:15:54,510
in Marks and Spencer's,
wouldn't you agree?

140
00:15:54,600 --> 00:15:57,478
-This isn't very good.
-I make a cocktail with crushed ice,

141
00:15:57,560 --> 00:16:01,075
rum and melted dark chocolate.
It's absolutely scrumptious.

142
00:16:07,640 --> 00:16:10,518
-LEON: Guess who we met on the way in?
-Robbie.

143
00:16:10,600 --> 00:16:13,558
-I told him to join us tonight.
-Oh, Leon, you didn't.

144
00:16:14,200 --> 00:16:19,274
So, Robbie, the housekeeper's son,
whose father did a bunk 20 years ago,

145
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:22,909
gets a scholarship to the local grammar,
the Old Man puts him through Cambridge,

146
00:16:23,000 --> 00:16:27,198
goes up at the same time as Cee, and
for three years she hardly speaks to him.

147
00:16:27,280 --> 00:16:29,236
Wouldn't let him within a mile
of her Roedean chums.

148
00:16:29,320 --> 00:16:31,117
Anyone got a cigarette?

149
00:16:31,200 --> 00:16:33,839
I don't know what the hell he's doing
these days, messing about in flower beds.

150
00:16:33,920 --> 00:16:35,990
As a matter of fact, he's planning on doing
a medical degree.

151
00:16:36,320 --> 00:16:38,629
LEON: And the Old Man said yes to that?

152
00:16:42,360 --> 00:16:45,079
Look, I really think you should go down
to the lodge and ask him not to come.

153
00:16:45,160 --> 00:16:47,754
Why? Has something happened
between you?

154
00:16:48,760 --> 00:16:50,239
For God's sake.

155
00:17:17,400 --> 00:17:20,312
-When can we go home?
-LOLA: Soon.

156
00:17:20,400 --> 00:17:22,550
We can't go home. It's a divorce.

157
00:17:24,920 --> 00:17:27,957
-How dare you say that?
-Well, it's true!

158
00:17:28,040 --> 00:17:31,396
LOLA: You will never, ever use that word
again! Do you understand?

159
00:17:32,240 --> 00:17:35,789
-Now what are we going to do?
-I'm always asking myself that.

160
00:17:35,880 --> 00:17:39,668
My name is Paul Marshall.
You must be the cousins from the north.

161
00:17:39,920 --> 00:17:41,831
-What are your names?
-Pierrot.

162
00:17:41,920 --> 00:17:44,115
-Jackson.
-What marvellous names.

163
00:17:45,040 --> 00:17:46,359
JACKSON: Do you know our parents?

164
00:17:46,440 --> 00:17:47,793
PAUL: Well, I've read
about them in the paper.

165
00:17:47,880 --> 00:17:52,237
-What exactly have you read about them?
-Oh, you know. The usual sort of nonsense.

166
00:17:52,320 --> 00:17:56,029
I'll thank you not to talk about this
in front of the children.

167
00:18:00,440 --> 00:18:02,317
Your parents
are absolutely wonderful people,

168
00:18:02,400 --> 00:18:06,518
that's quite clear, and they love you
and think about you all the time.

169
00:18:07,440 --> 00:18:09,032
Jolly nice slacks.

170
00:18:09,960 --> 00:18:11,632
We went to see a show
and I got them at Liberty's.

171
00:18:11,720 --> 00:18:14,871
-What was the show?
-Hamlet.

172
00:18:14,960 --> 00:18:18,270
Ah, yes. "To be or not to be."

173
00:18:23,320 --> 00:18:24,753
I like your shoes.

174
00:18:26,600 --> 00:18:32,072
Duckers in the Turl. They make
a wooden thing, shaped like your foot.

175
00:18:32,560 --> 00:18:34,073
Keep it forever.

176
00:18:35,080 --> 00:18:37,071
PIERROT: I'm starving. When's dinner?

177
00:18:38,200 --> 00:18:40,998
Well, I might be able to help you there,
if you can guess what I do for a living.

178
00:18:41,080 --> 00:18:43,548
-You've got a chocolate factory.
-Everyone knows that.

179
00:18:43,640 --> 00:18:46,359
Then it wasn't a guess, was it?

180
00:18:46,440 --> 00:18:50,228
There'll be one of these in every kit bag
of every soldier in the British Army.

181
00:18:50,320 --> 00:18:52,356
Sugar casing, so it won't melt.

182
00:18:52,440 --> 00:18:54,476
JACKSON: Why should they get free sweets?

183
00:18:54,560 --> 00:18:55,993
'Cause they'll be fighting for their country.

184
00:18:56,080 --> 00:18:58,310
Our daddy says
there isn't going to be a war.

185
00:18:58,400 --> 00:19:00,470
Your daddy is wrong.

186
00:19:02,200 --> 00:19:05,829
-Calling it the Army Amo.
-Amo, amas, amat.

187
00:19:05,920 --> 00:19:07,956
Top marks.

188
00:19:08,040 --> 00:19:12,397
It's boring how everything ends in "o."
"Polo" and "Aero."

189
00:19:12,480 --> 00:19:14,994
-And "Oxo" and "Brillo".
-Sounds as if you don't want it.

190
00:19:15,080 --> 00:19:18,072
Then I shall just have to give it
to your sister.

191
00:19:28,160 --> 00:19:29,195
PAUL: Bite it.

192
00:19:31,280 --> 00:19:32,952
You have to bite it.

193
00:19:41,280 --> 00:19:44,556
BRIONY: The Princess was well aware
of his remorseless wickedness.

194
00:19:44,640 --> 00:19:48,110
But that made it no easier to overcome
the voluminous love she felt

195
00:19:48,200 --> 00:19:51,237
in her heart for Sir Romulus.
The Princess knew instinctively

196
00:19:51,320 --> 00:19:53,276
that the one with red hair
was not to be trusted.

197
00:19:53,360 --> 00:19:56,636
As his young ward dived again
and again to the depths of the lake,

198
00:19:56,720 --> 00:20:00,759
in search of the enchanted chalice,
Sir Romulus twirled his luxuriant moustache.

199
00:20:00,840 --> 00:20:05,231
Sir Romulus rode with his two companions,
northwards, drawing ever closer

200
00:20:05,320 --> 00:20:06,514
to an effulgent sea.

201
00:20:06,600 --> 00:20:09,672
So heroic in manner,
he appeared so valiant in word

202
00:20:09,760 --> 00:20:10,988
(TYPEWRITER CLACKING)

203
00:20:11,080 --> 00:20:13,036
no one could ever guess at the darkness

204
00:20:13,120 --> 00:20:15,588
lurking in the black heart
of Sir Romulus Turnbull.

205
00:20:15,680 --> 00:20:18,478
He was the most dangerous man
in the world.

206
00:20:26,440 --> 00:20:29,750
"Dear Cecilia, I thought I should write
to apologise for my clumsy

207
00:20:29,840 --> 00:20:31,637
"and inconsiderate behaviour."

208
00:20:42,840 --> 00:20:44,432
(OPERA PLAYING)

209
00:21:57,480 --> 00:21:59,630
"Forgive me if I seem strange but I'm..."

210
00:22:55,200 --> 00:22:56,519
(CHUCKLING)

211
00:23:21,560 --> 00:23:25,553
ROBBIE: Dear Cecilia, you'd be forgiven
for thinking me mad,

212
00:23:25,640 --> 00:23:27,358
the way I acted this afternoon.

213
00:23:27,440 --> 00:23:31,319
The truth is I feel rather lightheaded
and foolish in your presence, Cee,

214
00:23:31,400 --> 00:23:33,630
and I don't think I can blame the heat.

215
00:23:35,320 --> 00:23:36,753
"Will you forgive me?

216
00:23:39,680 --> 00:23:40,908
"Robbie."

217
00:23:57,640 --> 00:23:59,153
Off out then?

218
00:23:59,240 --> 00:24:01,708
ROBBIE: Yes, Leon's asked me
to join them for dinner.

219
00:24:02,680 --> 00:24:06,070
So that's why I've been polishing
silver all afternoon.

220
00:24:06,160 --> 00:24:09,232
I'll think of you when I see my face
in the spoon.

221
00:24:12,680 --> 00:24:17,151
You're not a bit like your father.
Not in any way.

222
00:24:17,240 --> 00:24:19,959
That's because I'm all yours. I'll be late.

223
00:24:22,000 --> 00:24:24,309
Your shirts are hanging upstairs.

224
00:24:27,640 --> 00:24:29,676
-Son.
-Yes?

225
00:24:30,320 --> 00:24:31,673
Nothing.

226
00:25:22,120 --> 00:25:24,031
Briony! Is that you?

227
00:25:46,120 --> 00:25:47,599
Are you all right?

228
00:25:51,160 --> 00:25:53,355
Do you think you could do me a favour?

229
00:25:54,000 --> 00:25:57,117
Could you run ahead
and give this to Cee? I...

230
00:25:57,200 --> 00:26:01,716
-Feel a bit of a fool handing it over myself.
-All right.

231
00:26:26,440 --> 00:26:27,589
Briony.

232
00:26:53,400 --> 00:26:55,197
Briony!

233
00:26:55,440 --> 00:26:57,237
(PANTING)

234
00:27:14,360 --> 00:27:16,999
-I suppose he's what you might call eligible.
-Rather.

235
00:27:17,080 --> 00:27:19,150
He certainly seems to think
he's the cat's pyjamas.

236
00:27:19,240 --> 00:27:22,437
Which is odd, considering he has pubic hair
growing out of his ears.

237
00:27:22,520 --> 00:27:25,830
I should imagine he'd give you
a lot of very noisy, boneheaded sons.

238
00:27:25,920 --> 00:27:28,195
-He's quite a good egg, actually.
-You say that about everyone.

239
00:27:28,280 --> 00:27:31,909
-Leon!
-Rummy, if it ain't my little sis!

240
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:34,878
I wrote you a play, Leon.
I wanted to do a play for you.

241
00:27:34,960 --> 00:27:36,678
-The Trials Of Arabella.
-Well, there's still time.

242
00:27:36,760 --> 00:27:38,273
-Doesn't have to be this evening.
-No, it's impossible.

243
00:27:38,360 --> 00:27:39,713
CECILIA: Briony.
LEON: Tell you what. I'm good at voices,

244
00:27:39,800 --> 00:27:41,552
you're even better,
so we'll read it out after dinner.

245
00:27:41,640 --> 00:27:44,438
-Briony, did you read this letter?
-Yes, let's. That's a wonderful idea.

246
00:27:44,520 --> 00:27:48,752
-Briony!
-Here we are. My choc-tail.

247
00:27:49,240 --> 00:27:51,037
I insist you try it.

248
00:27:51,920 --> 00:27:53,751
Wasn't there an envelope?

249
00:28:00,960 --> 00:28:02,154
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

250
00:28:04,720 --> 00:28:06,358
Do you mind if I come in?

251
00:28:07,960 --> 00:28:10,235
LOLA: I've had the most appalling evening.

252
00:28:11,720 --> 00:28:14,154
The twins have been torturing me. Look.

253
00:28:14,240 --> 00:28:15,514
How awful.

254
00:28:18,520 --> 00:28:19,794
Chinese burns.

255
00:28:21,320 --> 00:28:23,197
That's right.

256
00:28:23,520 --> 00:28:28,150
They want to go home.
They think it's me that's keeping them here.

257
00:28:29,400 --> 00:28:30,992
(LOLA SOBBING)

258
00:28:33,760 --> 00:28:35,079
Lola.

259
00:28:35,760 --> 00:28:39,958
Can I tell you something?
Something really terrible.

260
00:28:40,040 --> 00:28:41,268
Yes, please.

261
00:28:42,080 --> 00:28:45,072
What's the worst word
you can possibly imagine?

262
00:28:52,800 --> 00:28:54,358
(BELL RINGING)

263
00:28:55,240 --> 00:28:57,390
-He's a sex maniac!
-That's right.

264
00:28:57,480 --> 00:28:58,913
-What's Cecilia going to do?
-I don't know.

265
00:28:59,000 --> 00:29:01,468
-You ought to call the police.
-Do you think so?

266
00:29:01,560 --> 00:29:04,154
He said he thought about it all day long.

267
00:29:04,240 --> 00:29:06,310
All you have to do is show them the letter.

268
00:29:06,400 --> 00:29:09,073
-You won't tell anyone, will you, promise?
-I promise.

269
00:29:09,160 --> 00:29:12,232
Good. If he found out,
there's no knowing what he might do.

270
00:29:12,320 --> 00:29:13,469
You're right.

271
00:29:15,640 --> 00:29:18,791
You better tidy your face.
I've still got to change.

272
00:29:21,040 --> 00:29:23,508
Thanks, Briony. You're a real brick.

273
00:30:13,320 --> 00:30:14,753
(MEN CHATTERING)

274
00:30:15,480 --> 00:30:17,311
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

275
00:31:35,520 --> 00:31:36,794
(PANTING)

276
00:31:39,200 --> 00:31:40,269
BRIONY: Cecilia!

277
00:31:57,760 --> 00:32:00,115
-It was a mistake.
-Briony read it.

278
00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:02,550
My God, I'm so sorry.
It was the wrong version.

279
00:32:02,640 --> 00:32:03,868
Yes.

280
00:32:07,560 --> 00:32:09,551
-It was never meant to be read.
-No.

281
00:32:28,640 --> 00:32:30,392
(CLOCK CHIMING)

282
00:32:43,400 --> 00:32:44,913
What was in the version
I was meant to read?

283
00:32:45,000 --> 00:32:46,877
I don't know. It was more formal. Less...

284
00:32:46,960 --> 00:32:48,518
-Anatomical?
-Yes.

285
00:32:54,880 --> 00:32:58,919
It's been there for weeks,
and then this morning by the fountain...

286
00:33:07,840 --> 00:33:10,593
I've never done anything like that before.

287
00:33:10,920 --> 00:33:13,753
And I was so angry with you,
and with myself.

288
00:33:16,480 --> 00:33:19,836
I thought if you went away to medical
school, then I'd be happy, but...

289
00:33:19,920 --> 00:33:23,356
I don't know how I could have been
so ignorant about myself, so...

290
00:33:27,120 --> 00:33:28,599
So stupid.

291
00:33:35,040 --> 00:33:37,759
You do know what I'm talking about,
don't you?

292
00:33:40,320 --> 00:33:43,039
You knew before I did.

293
00:33:44,640 --> 00:33:46,392
Why are you crying?

294
00:33:47,880 --> 00:33:49,438
Don't you know?

295
00:33:49,920 --> 00:33:51,592
Yes, I know exactly.

296
00:33:51,680 --> 00:33:52,715
(SIGHING)

297
00:34:54,080 --> 00:34:55,991
(BOTH MOANING)

298
00:35:31,640 --> 00:35:32,675
Robbie.

299
00:35:33,600 --> 00:35:34,635
Cecilia.

300
00:35:36,480 --> 00:35:37,549
I love you.

301
00:35:40,000 --> 00:35:41,319
I love you.

302
00:36:15,360 --> 00:36:17,351
(BOTH MOANING)

303
00:36:17,440 --> 00:36:18,555
(DOOR OPENING)

304
00:36:20,800 --> 00:36:22,392
Someone's come in.

305
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:25,194
Cecilia!

306
00:37:07,440 --> 00:37:09,317
LEON: People were sitting out
having dinner on the pavement.

307
00:37:09,400 --> 00:37:13,632
It was always the view of my parents
that hot weather encouraged loose morals.

308
00:37:13,720 --> 00:37:15,995
In high summer, my sister and l
were never allowed out of the house.

309
00:37:16,080 --> 00:37:19,629
They thought the villagers would be
unnecessarily provoked.

310
00:37:21,480 --> 00:37:25,189
What do you say, Cee? Does the hot weather
make you behave badly?

311
00:37:26,920 --> 00:37:29,753
-Good heavens, you're blushing.
-It's just hot in here, that's all.

312
00:37:29,840 --> 00:37:32,308
Lola, wipe that lipstick off.
You're far too young.

313
00:37:32,400 --> 00:37:35,949
What about you, Briony?
What sins have you committed today?

314
00:37:36,800 --> 00:37:39,951
-I've done nothing wrong.
-EMILY: Have you seen the twins recently?

315
00:37:40,080 --> 00:37:42,640
They didn't look very happy
last time I saw them, poor little chaps.

316
00:37:42,720 --> 00:37:45,951
-BRIONY: You know nothing about it.
-Briony. I can't imagine what's got into you.

317
00:37:46,040 --> 00:37:48,474
-I've never known you to be so rude.
-BRIONY: Well, they're not poor little chaps.

318
00:37:48,560 --> 00:37:50,596
-Just look what they did to Lola.
-What are you talking about?

319
00:37:50,680 --> 00:37:53,752
BRIONY: Jackson and Pierrot
bruised her arm. Gave her Chinese burns.

320
00:37:53,840 --> 00:37:55,671
I'm afraid she's quite right.
I had to pull them off her.

321
00:37:55,760 --> 00:37:57,990
How I got my war wound.

322
00:37:58,080 --> 00:37:59,433
The twins did that, Lola?

323
00:37:59,520 --> 00:38:01,317
PAUL: Yes, it all turned
into a bit of a wrestle,

324
00:38:01,400 --> 00:38:03,630
I'm afraid. Still, no harm done, eh, Lola?

325
00:38:03,720 --> 00:38:05,312
EMILY: Would you go and find these boys,
please, Briony?

326
00:38:05,400 --> 00:38:07,038
Tell them dinner's ready,
and where are their manners?

327
00:38:07,120 --> 00:38:08,951
-Why do I have to go?
-Briony, you'll do as you're told,

328
00:38:09,040 --> 00:38:11,429
or you'll go straight to your room.

329
00:38:39,360 --> 00:38:40,793
-BRIONY: It's a letter!
-Give it to me!

330
00:38:40,880 --> 00:38:42,393
BRIONY: They've run away.
EMILY: Who has?

331
00:38:42,480 --> 00:38:43,754
BRIONY: The twins.

332
00:38:44,640 --> 00:38:49,430
"We are going to run away because Lola
is so horrid to us and we want to go home.

333
00:38:51,040 --> 00:38:52,519
-"Also, there wasn't a play."
-Don't worry.

334
00:38:52,600 --> 00:38:54,750
We'll send out some search parties.
They can't have gone far.

335
00:38:54,840 --> 00:38:56,796
Cee, you come with me.

336
00:39:02,360 --> 00:39:03,395
LEON: Pierrot!

337
00:39:04,200 --> 00:39:05,235
CECILIA: Jackson!

338
00:39:06,400 --> 00:39:07,469
PAUL: Boys!

339
00:39:08,640 --> 00:39:09,675
Jackson!

340
00:39:11,800 --> 00:39:12,835
LEON: Pierrot!

341
00:39:29,560 --> 00:39:30,879
(RUSTLING)

342
00:39:55,200 --> 00:39:56,235
(SCREAMING)

343
00:40:36,640 --> 00:40:38,358
(GASPING)

344
00:40:45,720 --> 00:40:47,358
(LOLA SOBBING)

345
00:40:48,800 --> 00:40:50,756
Lola? Are you all right?

346
00:40:51,320 --> 00:40:54,039
I'm sorry. I didn't... I'm sorry.

347
00:40:54,120 --> 00:40:56,111
Who was it?

348
00:40:58,280 --> 00:40:59,554
I saw him.

349
00:41:00,560 --> 00:41:01,595
I saw him.

350
00:41:02,600 --> 00:41:04,750
-It was him, wasn't it?
-Yes, it was him.

351
00:41:04,840 --> 00:41:06,353
Lola, who was it?

352
00:41:08,400 --> 00:41:11,710
It was Robbie, wasn't it? Robbie?

353
00:41:13,440 --> 00:41:16,000
-You saw him?
-Like you said, he's a sex maniac.

354
00:41:16,080 --> 00:41:18,719
And you don't even know
what happened before dinner.

355
00:41:18,800 --> 00:41:20,313
I caught him attacking my sister
in the library.

356
00:41:20,400 --> 00:41:22,516
I don't know what he'd have done
if I hadn't come in.

357
00:41:22,600 --> 00:41:25,910
-You actually saw him?
-Of course I did. Plain as day.

358
00:41:27,680 --> 00:41:31,798
He pushed me to the ground.
And then he put his hands over my eyes.

359
00:41:32,920 --> 00:41:37,789
-I couldn't actually... I never actually...
-Listen. I've known him

360
00:41:37,880 --> 00:41:39,996
my whole life, and I saw him.

361
00:41:40,760 --> 00:41:43,035
Because I couldn't say for sure.

362
00:41:43,840 --> 00:41:46,434
Well, I can. And I will.

363
00:41:51,040 --> 00:41:54,476
LEON: Call the police.
And she'll be needing a doctor, as well.

364
00:42:01,920 --> 00:42:03,592
(LOLA SOBBING)

365
00:42:04,960 --> 00:42:09,078
-It's all right, dear. It's all right now.
-CECILIA: Is Robbie back yet?

366
00:42:09,160 --> 00:42:11,276
I haven't seen him.

367
00:42:11,680 --> 00:42:13,432
I know who it was.

368
00:42:15,800 --> 00:42:19,110
-You saw him, then?
-Yes, I saw him.

369
00:42:19,200 --> 00:42:22,112
-Just as you see me?
-I know it was him.

370
00:42:22,200 --> 00:42:25,431
You know it was him? Or you saw him?

371
00:42:26,720 --> 00:42:30,076
-Yes, I did, I saw him.
-With your own eyes?

372
00:42:31,040 --> 00:42:34,669
Yes. I saw him, I saw him with my own eyes.

373
00:42:38,480 --> 00:42:39,993
EMILY: Well done, darling.

374
00:43:29,480 --> 00:43:32,836
My brother and I found the two of them
down by the lake.

375
00:43:32,920 --> 00:43:34,956
POLICEMAN: You didn't see anyone else?

376
00:43:37,080 --> 00:43:41,596
I wouldn't necessarily believe everything
Briony tells you. She's rather fanciful.

377
00:43:49,480 --> 00:43:52,472
When they went looking,
I went up to my dad's.

378
00:43:52,560 --> 00:43:55,074
-I did, honest.
-POLICEMAN: Why was that?

379
00:43:56,320 --> 00:43:57,992
To tell him all about it.

380
00:43:59,960 --> 00:44:03,350
-I know I shouldn't have opened it.
-EMILY: No, you should not.

381
00:44:04,800 --> 00:44:07,633
But at least you've done the right thing now.

382
00:44:23,720 --> 00:44:25,073
(SNORING)

383
00:44:42,080 --> 00:44:43,991
(TAPPING PIANO KEY)

384
00:44:45,120 --> 00:44:47,236
Sir, there is someone coming.

385
00:45:15,280 --> 00:45:17,032
-Time you went to bed.
-But...

386
00:45:17,120 --> 00:45:18,189
Now.

387
00:46:19,320 --> 00:46:20,514
(DOOR OPENING)

388
00:46:28,200 --> 00:46:29,235
EMILY: Cecilia!

389
00:46:51,560 --> 00:46:55,997
You liars! You liars! Liars! Liars!

390
00:47:03,760 --> 00:47:05,318
(GRACE WAILING)

391
00:47:32,360 --> 00:47:34,191
(HARMONICA PLAYING)

392
00:47:34,280 --> 00:47:36,350
Northern France
Four years later

393
00:47:41,640 --> 00:47:44,996
NETTLE: I says to him, I says, "You can sit
down there, twiddling your thumbs,

394
00:47:45,080 --> 00:47:47,071
"waiting to get your head blown off,
if you want to.

395
00:47:47,160 --> 00:47:48,275
"I'm off out of it."

396
00:47:48,360 --> 00:47:49,475
(ROBBIE SHUSHING)

397
00:47:49,560 --> 00:47:50,959
(FLOOR CREAKING)

398
00:47:57,560 --> 00:48:01,348
MAN: Bonsoir monsieur. Bonsoir?
ROBBIE: (WHISPERING) Let me do this.

399
00:48:01,640 --> 00:48:03,392
(MAN 1 SPEAKING FRENCH)

400
00:48:04,360 --> 00:48:07,113
(ALL PANTING)

401
00:48:07,200 --> 00:48:08,553
(ROBBIE SPEAKING FRENCH)

402
00:48:15,960 --> 00:48:17,313
MACE: What's his game?

403
00:48:17,400 --> 00:48:19,595
-He says he's got something for us.
-Fucking hell!

404
00:48:19,680 --> 00:48:20,795
(MEN SPEAKING FRENCH)

405
00:48:20,880 --> 00:48:22,996
Wait! We have food for you

406
00:48:23,120 --> 00:48:24,189
Bread, sugar

407
00:48:24,280 --> 00:48:25,315
And wine!

408
00:48:30,880 --> 00:48:31,915
(SIGHING)

409
00:48:35,280 --> 00:48:36,872
What are you doing here?

410
00:48:38,600 --> 00:48:40,352
(MEN SPEAKING FRENCH)

411
00:48:42,880 --> 00:48:46,270
When the retreat started, Panzers attacked,

412
00:48:47,240 --> 00:48:49,310
and I was separated from my unit

413
00:48:49,480 --> 00:48:51,869
So it's true, the English are retreating

414
00:48:54,600 --> 00:48:57,160
We'll be gone at first light

415
00:48:58,640 --> 00:49:01,393
We fought all those years,
lost all those dead,

416
00:49:01,840 --> 00:49:04,229
now the Germans are in France again

417
00:49:07,640 --> 00:49:08,993
We will come back

418
00:49:11,080 --> 00:49:12,672
we will throw them out

419
00:49:14,440 --> 00:49:17,113
I promise you

420
00:49:18,440 --> 00:49:20,032
Good luck

421
00:49:24,840 --> 00:49:26,159
NETTLE: Come on, then.

422
00:49:26,240 --> 00:49:30,074
How come a toff like you, talks French
and everything, ends up a private?

423
00:49:30,160 --> 00:49:33,630
Not eligible for officers' training
if you join direct from prison.

424
00:49:33,800 --> 00:49:36,917
-You're pulling my tit.
-No, I'm not.

425
00:49:38,440 --> 00:49:41,750
They gave me a choice.
Stay in prison or join the Army.

426
00:49:42,760 --> 00:49:45,797
And for the record,
the last thing I am is a toff.

427
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:05,956
Six months earlier

428
00:50:20,280 --> 00:50:21,793
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

429
00:50:32,040 --> 00:50:33,473
I'm sorry I'm late, I got lost.

430
00:50:33,600 --> 00:50:35,272
-Hello.
-Hello.

431
00:50:44,640 --> 00:50:47,074
-Should we sit down?
-Yes, of course.

432
00:51:01,560 --> 00:51:04,597
-I'm sorry, I can't remember, l...
-Two. Thank you.

433
00:51:37,760 --> 00:51:39,557
Where are you living?

434
00:51:41,160 --> 00:51:43,390
Tiny flat in Balham. It's ghastly.

435
00:51:43,480 --> 00:51:46,631
-The landlady's rude and horribly nosy.
-You look the same.

436
00:51:46,720 --> 00:51:49,109
-Apart from the uniform, of course.
-Yes, I'm sorry. I've got to go back

437
00:51:49,200 --> 00:51:52,192
-to the hospital in half an hour.
-Oh, God, that...

438
00:52:12,680 --> 00:52:14,033
-Sorry.
-No.

439
00:52:18,000 --> 00:52:20,468
Have you been in touch with your family?

440
00:52:20,560 --> 00:52:22,516
No, I told you I wouldn't.

441
00:52:23,960 --> 00:52:26,235
Leon waited outside the hospital last week,
I just pushed past him.

442
00:52:26,320 --> 00:52:28,959
Cee, you don't owe me anything.

443
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:33,514
Robbie, didn't you read my letters?

444
00:52:33,920 --> 00:52:36,036
Had I been allowed to visit you,
had they let me every day,

445
00:52:36,120 --> 00:52:38,509
-I would have been there every day.
-Yes, but...

446
00:52:38,600 --> 00:52:42,036
If all we have rests on a few moments

447
00:52:42,120 --> 00:52:44,588
in a library three and a half years ago,
then I'm not sure,

448
00:52:44,680 --> 00:52:47,672
-I don't know if...
-Robbie, look at me.

449
00:52:50,720 --> 00:52:53,234
Look at me.

450
00:52:54,280 --> 00:52:55,599
(WHISPERS) Come back.

451
00:52:58,680 --> 00:53:00,318
Come back to me.

452
00:53:14,000 --> 00:53:15,672
ROBBIE: Dearest Cecilia.

453
00:53:17,320 --> 00:53:19,356
Dearest Cecilia.

454
00:53:26,320 --> 00:53:27,389
Cecilia.

455
00:53:42,280 --> 00:53:44,271
A friend of mine has a cottage by the coast.

456
00:53:44,360 --> 00:53:46,590
Said we can borrow it
when you're next on leave.

457
00:53:46,680 --> 00:53:49,672
White clapboard
with blue-painted window frames.

458
00:53:51,400 --> 00:53:54,631
-I hope this bus never comes.
-Here.

459
00:53:56,720 --> 00:53:59,439
Something to think of while you're away.

460
00:54:20,960 --> 00:54:22,029
I love you.

461
00:55:20,880 --> 00:55:21,869
(SIGHS)

462
00:55:45,200 --> 00:55:46,633
(PLANES DRONING)

463
00:55:49,080 --> 00:55:51,150
Some poor sod's gonna catch a packet.

464
00:55:59,360 --> 00:56:03,433
CECILIA: My darling. Briony found
my address somehow, and sent a letter.

465
00:56:04,600 --> 00:56:07,239
The first surprise was
she didn't go up to Cambridge.

466
00:56:07,320 --> 00:56:09,993
She's doing nurse's training
at my old hospital.

467
00:56:11,160 --> 00:56:13,833
I think she may be doing this
as some kind of penance.

468
00:56:13,920 --> 00:56:18,436
She says she's beginning to get the full
grasp of what she did, and what it meant.

469
00:56:18,560 --> 00:56:20,949
She wants to come and talk to me.

470
00:56:22,240 --> 00:56:26,791
I love you. I'll wait for you. Come back.

471
00:56:28,160 --> 00:56:29,195
Come back to me.

472
00:56:30,480 --> 00:56:32,789
ROBBIE: Come back. Come back to me.

473
00:56:33,800 --> 00:56:36,837
Come back. Come back to me.

