(BOTH SPEAKING IN FRENCH)

715
01:26:16,160 --> 01:26:17,593
Here you are at last

716
01:26:18,440 --> 01:26:19,998
Sister sent me

717
01:26:20,080 --> 01:26:22,230
for a little chat

718
01:26:24,960 --> 01:26:27,110
I remember your sister

719
01:26:27,600 --> 01:26:30,034
she was always so nice

720
01:26:31,680 --> 01:26:33,193
what's she doing now?

721
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:38,197
She is a nurse as well

722
01:26:39,200 --> 01:26:42,192
Did she finally marry that man
she was so in love with?

723
01:26:42,840 --> 01:26:44,193
I've forgotten his name

724
01:26:44,280 --> 01:26:45,315
Robbie?

725
01:26:47,000 --> 01:26:48,433
She will soon I hope

726
01:26:49,360 --> 01:26:50,395
Robbie

727
01:26:51,000 --> 01:26:52,752
yes that's right

728
01:26:54,960 --> 01:26:55,995
And you?

729
01:26:56,320 --> 01:26:57,799
What is your name?

730
01:26:59,920 --> 01:27:00,909
Luc.

731
01:27:02,360 --> 01:27:03,713
Luc Cornet.

732
01:27:05,840 --> 01:27:07,034
And you?

733
01:27:07,120 --> 01:27:08,155
Tallis.

734
01:27:09,520 --> 01:27:10,509
Tallis.

735
01:27:12,280 --> 01:27:14,111
That's pretty

736
01:27:18,840 --> 01:27:21,354
I remember you now

737
01:27:23,240 --> 01:27:25,276
the English girl

738
01:27:26,440 --> 01:27:29,113
You remember your first visit to Millau?

739
01:27:30,400 --> 01:27:32,834
I was working by the ovens with my father.

740
01:27:33,800 --> 01:27:35,870
I heard your accent

741
01:27:39,840 --> 01:27:42,479
Can you do me a little favour Tallis?

742
01:27:44,320 --> 01:27:46,880
These bandages are so tight,

743
01:27:47,200 --> 01:27:50,192
can you loosen them a bit, please?

744
01:27:51,280 --> 01:27:52,633
Of course

745
01:28:00,200 --> 01:28:02,430
You remember my younger sister, Anne?

746
01:28:04,760 --> 01:28:07,672
She still plays that little Debussy piece

747
01:28:09,360 --> 01:28:10,713
do you remember?

748
01:28:13,000 --> 01:28:15,958
She looks so serious when she plays

749
01:28:17,040 --> 01:28:18,837
And our croissants,

750
01:28:19,440 --> 01:28:21,192
what did you think of them?

751
01:28:28,520 --> 01:28:30,590
The most delicious in Millau

752
01:28:31,000 --> 01:28:31,989
Yes.

753
01:28:32,200 --> 01:28:34,236
it's the quality of the butter

754
01:28:35,880 --> 01:28:36,869
Yes

755
01:28:40,240 --> 01:28:42,595
Is that why you came every day?

756
01:28:44,000 --> 01:28:45,513
Because you know,

757
01:28:47,400 --> 01:28:50,710
my mother is very fond of you

758
01:28:51,400 --> 01:28:53,038
in her opinion,

759
01:28:53,520 --> 01:28:56,159
we should get married in the summer

760
01:28:56,520 --> 01:28:57,919
Oh yes?

761
01:28:58,160 --> 01:28:59,593
Yes

762
01:29:07,240 --> 01:29:09,515
I hope that's more comfortable

763
01:29:14,240 --> 01:29:15,229
Do you love me?

764
01:29:15,320 --> 01:29:17,231
Yes

765
01:29:25,280 --> 01:29:27,635
Can you stay a while?

766
01:29:29,080 --> 01:29:31,992
I'm frightened

767
01:29:40,960 --> 01:29:42,518
-Tallis.
-Briony.

768
01:29:44,200 --> 01:29:45,918
Je m'appelle Briony.

769
01:29:57,280 --> 01:29:59,271
SISTER: Stand up, Nurse Tallis.

770
01:30:04,040 --> 01:30:06,679
Now go and wash the blood off your face.

771
01:31:06,000 --> 01:31:10,755
NARRATOR: The Navy has earned our
undying gratitude. The Army is undefeated.

772
01:31:10,840 --> 01:31:14,435
Courage has brought them through
unconquered, their spirit unbowed.

773
01:31:14,520 --> 01:31:16,511
This is the epic of Dunkirk.

774
01:31:16,600 --> 01:31:20,673
A name that will live forever
in the annals of warfare.

775
01:31:24,280 --> 01:31:26,396
In the course of a comprehensive tour,

776
01:31:26,480 --> 01:31:30,075
Queen Elizabeth is seen here visiting
a chocolate factory in the north of England.

777
01:31:30,160 --> 01:31:32,390
The confectionary magnate
and friend of the British Army,

778
01:31:32,480 --> 01:31:36,553
Mr Paul Marshall, gave the Queen a tour
of the Army Amo factory

779
01:31:36,640 --> 01:31:40,838
with his lovely,
soon-to-be-wed fiance, Miss Lola Quincey.

780
01:31:40,920 --> 01:31:43,559
What a mouthwatering couple they are.

781
01:31:43,680 --> 01:31:47,070
Keep the Amo coming.
Our boys have a sweet tooth.

782
01:32:13,560 --> 01:32:19,271
Secondly, for a remedy against sin,
and to avoid fornication,

783
01:32:19,360 --> 01:32:23,069
that such persons
as have not the gift of continence,

784
01:32:23,160 --> 01:32:28,518
might marry and keep themselves
undefiled members of Christ's body.

785
01:32:29,320 --> 01:32:34,314
Thirdly, it was ordained,
for the mutual society, help and comfort,

786
01:32:34,400 --> 01:32:37,790
that the one ought to have the other.

787
01:32:37,880 --> 01:32:38,949
I saw him.

788
01:32:39,040 --> 01:32:42,794
Therefore, if any man can show
any just cause

789
01:32:42,880 --> 01:32:45,713
why they may not be
lawfully joined together...

790
01:32:45,880 --> 01:32:46,869
I know it was him.

791
01:32:47,120 --> 01:32:52,353
...Iet him now speak
or forever hold his peace.

792
01:32:55,720 --> 01:32:56,709
(GASPS)

793
01:32:58,680 --> 01:33:01,274
I saw him. I saw him with my own eyes.

794
01:33:01,360 --> 01:33:03,396
(ORGAN PLAYING)

795
01:33:41,960 --> 01:33:43,598
WOMAN: Let the nursey through.

796
01:33:43,680 --> 01:33:46,069
They're going down to the country today.
Never been out of London before.

797
01:33:46,160 --> 01:33:47,309
I hope they get a nice family.

798
01:33:47,400 --> 01:33:49,550
They don't know what they're in for
with this lot.

799
01:33:49,640 --> 01:33:50,675
Come on.

800
01:34:08,040 --> 01:34:10,998
I'm looking for Miss Tallis. Cecilia Tallis.

801
01:34:12,360 --> 01:34:13,395
Is she in?

802
01:34:19,280 --> 01:34:21,669
Tallis! Door!

803
01:34:29,160 --> 01:34:31,310
I tried writing. You wouldn't answer.

804
01:34:36,120 --> 01:34:37,917
I have to talk to you.

805
01:34:44,680 --> 01:34:45,715
(DOOR CLOSING)

806
01:35:01,560 --> 01:35:03,835
-So you're a ward sister now?
-Yes.

807
01:35:16,680 --> 01:35:17,715
Thanks.

808
01:35:26,720 --> 01:35:28,676
I want to go in front of a judge
and change my evidence, Cee.

809
01:35:28,760 --> 01:35:30,398
Don't call me that.

810
01:35:35,800 --> 01:35:37,711
Please don't call me that.

811
01:35:40,560 --> 01:35:42,835
I know what I did was terrible.
I don't expect you to forgive me.

812
01:35:42,920 --> 01:35:44,876
Oh, don't worry, I won't.

813
01:35:46,920 --> 01:35:49,354
You're an unreliable witness.
They'll never reopen the case.

814
01:35:49,440 --> 01:35:51,112
Well, at least
I could tell everyone else what I did.

815
01:35:51,200 --> 01:35:53,509
I can go home and explain
to Mummy and Daddy and Leon...

816
01:35:53,600 --> 01:35:55,750
-So what's stopping you?
-Well, I wanted to see you first.

817
01:35:55,840 --> 01:35:57,956
They don't want to hear any more about it.

818
01:35:58,040 --> 01:36:01,112
That unpleasantness is all tidied away
in the past, thank you very much.

819
01:36:01,200 --> 01:36:02,269
But...

820
01:36:09,960 --> 01:36:12,110
I'll be late. Better get moving.

821
01:36:15,520 --> 01:36:16,794
Excuse me.

822
01:36:22,920 --> 01:36:24,717
He sleeps so deeply.

823
01:37:22,520 --> 01:37:25,717
-What is she doing here?
-She wanted to speak to me.

824
01:37:25,800 --> 01:37:27,597
Oh, yes, what about?

825
01:37:27,680 --> 01:37:28,999
The terrible thing I did.

826
01:37:29,080 --> 01:37:30,513
Robbie. Darling.

827
01:37:31,080 --> 01:37:33,992
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

828
01:37:34,360 --> 01:37:36,271
I'll be quite honest with you.

829
01:37:36,360 --> 01:37:37,759
I'm torn between breaking your neck here

830
01:37:37,840 --> 01:37:40,718
and taking you
and throwing you down the stairs.

831
01:37:40,800 --> 01:37:41,869
Oh, God.

832
01:37:41,960 --> 01:37:45,873
Do you have any idea what it's like in jail?
Of course, you don't.

833
01:37:46,240 --> 01:37:48,708
Tell me, did it give you pleasure
to think of me inside?

834
01:37:48,800 --> 01:37:50,552
-No.
-But you did nothing about it.

835
01:37:50,640 --> 01:37:52,278
-No.
-Do you think I assaulted your cousin?

836
01:37:52,360 --> 01:37:53,395
-No.
-Did you think it then?

837
01:37:53,480 --> 01:37:54,515
Yes. But yes and no.

838
01:37:54,600 --> 01:37:56,431
-And what's made you so certain now?
-Growing up.

839
01:37:56,520 --> 01:37:57,999
-Growing up?
-I was 13.

840
01:37:58,080 --> 01:38:01,117
How old do you have to be to know
the difference between right and wrong?

841
01:38:01,200 --> 01:38:02,553
What are you, 18?

842
01:38:02,640 --> 01:38:05,393
Do you have to be 18 before
you can bring yourself to own up to a lie?

843
01:38:05,480 --> 01:38:09,393
There are soldiers of 18, old enough
to be left to die by the side of the road,

844
01:38:09,480 --> 01:38:10,833
-did you know that?
-Yes.

845
01:38:10,920 --> 01:38:13,115
Five years ago,
you didn't care about telling the truth.

846
01:38:13,200 --> 01:38:16,397
You, all your family, you just assumed
that for all my education,

847
01:38:16,480 --> 01:38:19,472
I was still little better than a servant.
Still not to be trusted!

848
01:38:19,560 --> 01:38:22,472
Thanks to you, they were able to close ranks
and throw me to the fucking wolves!

849
01:38:22,560 --> 01:38:25,438
-Robbie! Look at me, look at me.
-Don't!

850
01:38:25,520 --> 01:38:28,990
Come back. Come back.

851
01:38:31,440 --> 01:38:33,590
Come back to me.

852
01:38:56,640 --> 01:38:57,675
CECILIA: Briony.

853
01:38:59,480 --> 01:39:01,118
There isn't much time.

854
01:39:02,320 --> 01:39:05,915
Robbie has to report for duty at 6:00,
and he's got a train to catch.

855
01:39:07,520 --> 01:39:08,794
So sit down.

856
01:39:14,480 --> 01:39:17,119
There are some things
you're going to do for us.

857
01:39:33,240 --> 01:39:34,912
You'll go to your parents
as soon as you can,

858
01:39:35,000 --> 01:39:36,319
and you'll tell them everything
they need to know

859
01:39:36,400 --> 01:39:39,312
to be convinced
that the evidence you gave was false.

860
01:39:39,400 --> 01:39:40,992
You'll meet with a solicitor,
make a statement,

861
01:39:41,080 --> 01:39:43,150
have it signed, witnessed,
send copies to us. Is that clear?

862
01:39:43,240 --> 01:39:44,309
Yes.

863
01:39:44,400 --> 01:39:47,119
You'll write a detailed letter to me
explaining everything that happened

864
01:39:47,200 --> 01:39:49,111
leading up to you saying
you saw me by the lake.

865
01:39:49,200 --> 01:39:50,394
Try to include whatever you can remember

866
01:39:50,480 --> 01:39:52,198
of what Danny Hardman was doing
that night.

867
01:39:52,280 --> 01:39:53,474
-Hardman?
-Yes.

868
01:39:56,560 --> 01:39:58,152
It wasn't Danny Hardman.

869
01:39:59,000 --> 01:40:00,911
It was Leon's friend, Marshall.

870
01:40:01,720 --> 01:40:02,755
I don't believe you.

871
01:40:02,840 --> 01:40:05,957
He's married Lola.
I've just come from their wedding.

872
01:40:11,720 --> 01:40:14,280
Lola won't be able to testify
against him now.

873
01:40:14,560 --> 01:40:16,516
(BREATHING DEEPLY)

874
01:40:16,600 --> 01:40:17,953
He's immune.

875
01:40:33,080 --> 01:40:37,631
I'm very, very sorry for the terrible distress
that I have caused.

876
01:40:39,560 --> 01:40:41,710
I am very, very sorry.

877
01:40:42,240 --> 01:40:44,151
ROBBIE: Just do as we've asked of you.

878
01:40:44,520 --> 01:40:48,798
Write it all down, just the truth, no rhymes.
No embellishments, no adjectives.

879
01:40:50,480 --> 01:40:52,152
And then leave us be.

880
01:40:54,000 --> 01:40:55,353
I will, I promise.

881
01:41:04,880 --> 01:41:05,915
(DOOR CLOSING)

882
01:41:55,600 --> 01:41:57,716
BRIONY: I'm sorry.
Could we stop for a moment?

883
01:41:59,040 --> 01:42:00,598
MAN: Of course. Is something the matter?

884
01:42:00,680 --> 01:42:03,797
I just need a couple of minutes by myself.

885
01:42:04,440 --> 01:42:05,998
(TAPE REWINDING)

886
01:42:06,080 --> 01:42:07,832
...minutes by myself.

887
01:42:09,200 --> 01:42:14,354
MAN: Briony Tallis, your new novel,
your twenty-first, is called Atonement. It's...

888
01:42:16,160 --> 01:42:17,195
Briony?

889
01:42:22,200 --> 01:42:24,316
I'm sorry. Could we stop for a moment?

890
01:42:58,120 --> 01:43:02,113
Briony Tallis, I'd like to talk now
about your new novel, Atonement,

891
01:43:02,200 --> 01:43:05,636
which comes out in a few days
to coincide with your birthday.

892
01:43:06,200 --> 01:43:10,432
-It's your twenty-first novel...
-It's my last novel.

893
01:43:11,920 --> 01:43:14,388
Oh, really? Are you retiring?

894
01:43:15,560 --> 01:43:16,834
I'm dying.

895
01:43:18,960 --> 01:43:22,999
My doctor tells me
I have something called vascular dementia,

896
01:43:24,560 --> 01:43:27,518
which is essentially
a continuous series of tiny strokes.

897
01:43:27,600 --> 01:43:32,993
Your brain closes down, gradually
you lose words, you lose your memory,

898
01:43:33,080 --> 01:43:35,992
which for a writer is pretty much the point.

899
01:43:38,720 --> 01:43:43,157
So that's why I could finally write the book,
I think. I had to.

900
01:43:43,960 --> 01:43:46,190
And why, of course, it's my last novel.

901
01:43:49,280 --> 01:43:50,759
Strangely enough,

902
01:43:55,440 --> 01:43:59,592
it would be just as accurate
to call it my first novel.

903
01:44:00,720 --> 01:44:05,714
I wrote several drafts as far back as my time
at St Thomas' Hospital during the War.

904
01:44:06,480 --> 01:44:08,869
I just couldn't ever find the way to do it.

905
01:44:09,640 --> 01:44:11,995
MAN: Because the novel is autobiographical,
is that right?

906
01:44:12,080 --> 01:44:15,436
Yes, entirely. I haven't changed any names,
including my own.

907
01:44:15,520 --> 01:44:17,272
And was that the problem?

908
01:44:18,560 --> 01:44:19,629
No.

909
01:44:20,480 --> 01:44:25,031
I had, for a very long time,
decided to tell the absolute truth.

910
01:44:26,480 --> 01:44:28,550
No rhymes, no embellishments.

911
01:44:37,200 --> 01:44:38,474
And I think...

912
01:44:41,400 --> 01:44:43,914
You've read the book,
you'll understand why.

913
01:44:45,840 --> 01:44:49,913
I got first-hand accounts of all the events
I didn't personally witness,

914
01:44:50,520 --> 01:44:55,275
the conditions in prison,
the evacuation to Dunkirk, everything.

915
01:44:56,720 --> 01:44:59,792
But the effect of all this honesty
was rather pitiless.

916
01:44:59,880 --> 01:45:05,716
You see, I couldn't any longer imagine
what purpose would be served by it.

917
01:45:07,160 --> 01:45:09,628
By what? Sorry. Served by honesty?

918
01:45:09,720 --> 01:45:10,789
By honesty.

919
01:45:12,120 --> 01:45:13,394
Or reality.

920
01:45:18,640 --> 01:45:20,437
Because, in fact,

921
01:45:21,720 --> 01:45:26,236
I was too much of a coward
to go and see my sister in June, 1940.

922
01:45:27,960 --> 01:45:29,678
I never made that journey to Balham.

923
01:45:29,760 --> 01:45:31,352
ROBBIE: Do you have any idea
what it's like in jail?

924
01:45:31,440 --> 01:45:33,396
BRIONY: So the scene in which
I confess to them is imagined.

925
01:45:33,480 --> 01:45:34,549
CECILIA: He sleeps so deeply.

926
01:45:34,640 --> 01:45:35,629
BRIONY: Invented.

927
01:45:35,720 --> 01:45:38,518
ROBBIE: How old do you have to be to know
the difference between right and wrong?

928
01:45:38,600 --> 01:45:40,955
BRIONY: And, in fact,
could never have happened.

929
01:45:41,040 --> 01:45:42,075
Because

930
01:45:44,400 --> 01:45:49,110
Robbie Turner died of septicaemia
at Bray-Dunes

931
01:45:50,200 --> 01:45:52,430
on June the first, 1940,

932
01:45:53,440 --> 01:45:55,431
the last day of the evacuation.

933
01:46:00,120 --> 01:46:01,269
Cheerio, pal.

934
01:46:33,720 --> 01:46:37,599
And I was never able to put things right
with my sister, Cecilia,

935
01:46:39,280 --> 01:46:43,671
because she was killed
on the 15th of October, 1940,

936
01:46:44,000 --> 01:46:48,152
by the bomb that destroyed the gas
and water mains above Balham tube station.

937
01:46:48,240 --> 01:46:50,037
(BOMBS EXPLODING)

938
01:47:23,400 --> 01:47:24,435
So...

939
01:47:26,880 --> 01:47:30,429
My sister and Robbie were never able
to have the time together

940
01:47:31,960 --> 01:47:35,919
they both so longed for, and deserved.

941
01:47:37,640 --> 01:47:40,393
And which, ever since, I've...

942
01:47:45,280 --> 01:47:49,353
Ever since I've always felt I prevented.

943
01:47:55,680 --> 01:47:58,672
But what sense of hope,

944
01:48:00,200 --> 01:48:04,478
or satisfaction, could a reader derive
from an ending like that?

945
01:48:05,280 --> 01:48:11,549
So, in the book, I wanted to give Robbie
and Cecilia what they lost out on in life.

946
01:48:12,880 --> 01:48:17,908
I'd like to think
this isn't weakness or evasion,

947
01:48:20,440 --> 01:48:22,476
but a final act of kindness.

948
01:48:24,200 --> 01:48:30,673
I gave them their happiness.

949
01:49:14,080 --> 01:49:16,719
(BOTH LAUGHING)

